ear of death.Resonating with Oz’s clear, honest, and humorous speaking voice, What Makes an Apple? offers a rare perspective on how Oz evolved as a person and a writer throughout his life, and enables readers to explore his work in new ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAuthors, Israeliy20th centuryvInterviews. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aA. B. Yehoshua.  aAbortion.  aAcross the Bridge (short story).  aAmmunition.  aAmos Oz.  aArabs.  aAwareness.  aBattle of Borodino.  aBerl Katznelson.  aBiblical Hebrew.  aBlackmail.  aBnei Brak.  aBohemianism.  aBook review.  aCaptain Nemo.  aCaregiver.  aCaricature.  aChutzpah.  aCity Of.  aCoercion.  aConsent.  aContraction (grammar).  aCripple.  aCriticism.  aCrutch.  aCursive.  aDiaper.  aEnthusiasm.  aEternal Happiness.  aEtgar Keret.  aFarce.  aFemininity.  aForgive Me (TV series).  aFranz Kafka.  aFurniture.  aGabardine.  aGenerosity.  aGeorge Bernard Shaw.  aGiza.  aGranary.  aGreater Israel.  aGrocery store.  aHalf-truth.  aHatred.  aHormone.  aHumiliation.  aI Wish (manhwa).  aIdiot.  aIncome.  aInfantilization.  aIsraelis.  aJews.  aKibbutz.  aKindergarten.  aLiteracy.  aLunch.  aMadame Bovary.  aMark Twain.  aMarket stall.  aMasculinity.  aMezuzah.  aMicrophone.  aMind control.  aMishnaic Hebrew.  aMitzvah.  aModern Hebrew.  aMy Day.  aMy Michael (novel).  aNicholas de Lange.  aNipple.  aNovelist.  aObjectification.  aOp-ed.  aOpinion piece.  aOrientalism.  aPaul Gauguin.  aPity.  aPoetry.  aPrivatization.  aProse.  aRevised Version.  aSchool of thought.  aSculpture.  aSelf-esteem.  aSeoul.  aSeriousness.  aSpider.  aState of Palestine.  aSweater.  aTendril.  aThe Newspape